ted refusals</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>:</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>:</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>:</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>:</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>20</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>1</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>6</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>38</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>36</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>32</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>z = Not applicable.</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>: = not available</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="12"><p>Source: Home Office, Immigration Statistics July to September 2017, tables se_01, se_02 and corresponding datasets</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Information on grants and refusals of settlement (permanent residence) are published in the Home Office’s ‘Immigration Statistics’, settlement tables se_01 and se_02, available on the GOV.UK website.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-12-21T16:48:34.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809614/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809614/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809614/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-12-19","Refugees","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how many refugees have (1) been granted permanent residence status, and (2) had their applications rejected, in each of the last ten years.","false","Biography information for Lord Marlesford",,"Lord Marlesford","HL4317"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809615","Home Office","false","2018-01-05","<p>Annex 6 of the Impact Assessment for the Immigration and Nationality (Fees) Order 2016 gives an estimate of the cost to the public purse of different migrant categories.</p><p> </p><p>Table 14: Estimate of the typical public service costs associated with various migrants (2014/15)</p><table><tbody><tr><td> </td><td>£ per head - Low case</td><td>£ per head - Central case</td><td>£ per head - High case</td></tr><tr><td>All migrants</td><td>5,300</td><td>7,000</td><td>8,800</td></tr><tr><td>Non-EEA migrants</td><td>5,400</td><td>7,100</td><td>8,900</td></tr><tr><td>Migrant in last 10 years</td><td>4,500</td><td>6,300</td><td>8,100</td></tr><tr><td>Migrant in last 5 years</td><td>4,300</td><td>4,300</td><td>4,300</td></tr><tr><td>Non EEA - Those who came to work;</td><td>5,300</td><td>7,100</td><td>8,800</td></tr><tr><td>Non EEA - Those who came to study</td><td>4,600</td><td>6,400</td><td>8,200</td></tr><tr><td>Non EEA - Those who came for family reasons</td><td>5,500</td><td>7,200</td><td>9,000</td></tr><tr><td>Non EEA - Those who came as a dependant;</td><td>5,400</td><td>7,100</td><td>8,900</td></tr><tr><td>Non EEA - Those who came to seek asylum.</td><td>5,700</td><td>7,500</td><td>9,200</td></tr></tbody></table><p>Source: HO calculations based upon ONS mid-year population estimates (2014), HM Treasury's Public Expenditure Statistical Analyses (PESA), (2015:Table 5.2), and the Annual Population Survey (Jan-Dec 2013). Rounding: nearest £100</p><p>Under our existing family reunion policy, we have granted over 24,000 visas to nuclear family members of refugees in the last five years. We therefore believe that the impact of the Bill would increase the costs to the public purse significantly because it would widen the definition of a family member of a refugee and enable a large number of extended family members to qualify to come to the UK and have access to public services. The Government’s priority is to provide international protection to people who need it and extending the scope of family reunion to extended family members who may themselves not need international protection would not achieve that.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","HL4321","2018-01-05T14:45:51.413Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809615/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809615/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809615/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-12-19","Refugees","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what is the average cost to public funds in the first year for a person who has been granted refugee status.","false","Biography information for Lord Marlesford",,"Lord Marlesford","HL4318"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809616","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-01-08","<p>The Insolvency Service regularly assesses how changes in debt levels impact on the number of personal insolvencies. It considers a wide range of economic indicators to determine which has the greater impact on levels of personal insolvency. Over the last five years, the analysis has shown that total household debt is a better indicator of personal insolvency movements than levels of credit card debt.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2018-01-08T15:45:16.33Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809616/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809616/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809616/answer",,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-12-19","Credit Cards: Debts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment he has made of the contribution of credit card debt to personal insolvency over the last five years.","false","Biography information for Stella Creasy","Walthamstow","Stella Creasy","120254"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809617","Home Office","false","2017-12-21","<p>Information on the total number of Family: Other visa applications and grants is published quarterly.</p><p>The most recent data can be found in the Home Office publication ‘Immigration Statistics, July – September 2017’. A breakdown of Family: Other visa grants by year are provided in the table below.</p><p>Entry clearance visas granted by category and country of nationality: Family: Other</p><table><tbody><tr><td>Year</td><td>Granted</td></tr><tr><td>2007</td><td>4,497</td></tr><tr><td>2008</td><td>3,632</td></tr><tr><td>2009</td><td>4,209</td></tr><tr><td>2010</td><td>4,887</td></tr><tr><td>2011</td><td>4,306</td></tr><tr><td>2012</td><td>3,710</td></tr><tr><td>2013</td><td>4,211</td></tr><tr><td>2014</td><td>4,596</td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td>4,887</td></tr><tr><td><p>2016</p></td><td>6,098</td></tr><tr><td><p>Q1-Q3 2017</p></td><td>3,801</td></tr></tbody></table><p>Source: Home Office Immigration Statistics July to September 2017, Table vi_01_q</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-12-21T16:49:44.707Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809617/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809617/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809617/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-12-19","Refugees: Families","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how many partners and children have been reunited with their refugee family members under the immigration rules and family reunion policy in each of the last ten years.","false","Biography information for Lord Marlesford",,"Lord Marlesford","HL4319"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809618","Home Office","false","2018-01-05","<p>In 2010 the Coalition Government decided to scrap the National Identity Register which would have used a National Identity Number to link individuals to a range of data items, including biometric data, that would have been collected and stored in a central database. This decision was taken because the National Identity Register was both expensive and represented a substantial erosion of civil liberties and this Government is not planning to revisit that decision.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2018-01-05T14:46:38.803Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809618/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809618/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809618/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-12-19","Proof of Identity","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they will consider the cost and method of introducing a secure national identity number, with electronic links to a centrally held register of biometric data, for all UK citizens.","false","Biography information for Lord Marlesford",,"Lord Marlesford","HL4320"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809619","Cabinet Office","false","2018-01-08","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2018-01-08T11:40:39.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809619/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809619/answer","PQ120255 UKSA .pdf","UKSA Response ","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809619/answer",,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-12-19","Older Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what the change in numbers has been of people aged 65 and over in (a) full-time and (b) part-time work over the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","120255"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809620","Home Office","false","2018-01-05","<p>Annex 6 of the Impact Assessment for the Immigration and Nationality (Fees) Order 2016 gives an estimate of the cost to the public purse of different migrant categories.</p><p> </p><p>Table 14: Estimate of the typical public service costs associated with various migrants (2014/15)</p><table><tbody><tr><td> </td><td>£ per head - Low case</td><td>£ per head - Central case</td><td>£ per head - High case</td></tr><tr><td>All migrants</td><td>5,300</td><td>7,000</td><td>8,800</td></tr><tr><td>Non-EEA migrants</td><td>5,400</td><td>7,100</td><td>8,900</td></tr><tr><td>Migrant in last 10 years</td><td>4,500</td><td>6,300</td><td>8,100</td></tr><tr><td>Migrant in last 5 years</td><td>4,300</td><td>4,300</td><td>4,300</td></tr><tr><td>Non EEA - Those who came to work;</td><td>5,300</td><td>7,100</td><td>8,800</td></tr><tr><td>Non EEA - Those who came to study</td><td>4,600</td><td>6,400</td><td>8,200</td></tr><tr><td>Non EEA - Those who came for family reasons</td><td>5,500</td><td>7,200</td><td>9,000</td></tr><tr><td>Non EEA - Those who came as a dependant;</td><td>5,400</td><td>7,100</td><td>8,900</td></tr><tr><td>Non EEA - Those who came to seek asylum.</td><td>5,700</td><td>7,500</td><td>9,200</td></tr></tbody></table><p>Source: HO calculations based upon ONS mid-year population estimates (2014), HM Treasury's Public Expenditure Statistical Analyses (PESA), (2015:Table 5.2), and the Annual Population Survey (Jan-Dec 2013). Rounding: nearest £100</p><p>Under our existing family reunion policy, we have granted over 24,000 visas to nuclear family members of refugees in the last five years. We therefore believe that the impact of the Bill would increase the costs to the public purse significantly because it would widen the definition of a family member of a refugee and enable a large number of extended family members to qualify to come to the UK and have access to public services. The Government’s priority is to provide international protection to people who need it and extending the scope of family reunion to extended family members who may themselves not need international protection would not achieve that.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","HL4318","2018-01-05T14:45:51.38Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809620/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809620/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809620/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-12-19","Refugees: Families","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they have estimated the cost to public funds, and the impact on the availability of medical care, housing and education, of passing the Refugee (Family Reunion) Bill.","false","Biography information for Lord Marlesford",,"Lord Marlesford","HL4321"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809621","HM Treasury","false","2018-01-05","<p>The Government has issued many loans over the years and interest rates have varied considerably over time. Given this, details of all loans issued and the rates applied are not held centrally by HM Treasury.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2018-01-05T13:05:17.55Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809621/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809621/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809621/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-12-19","Government Departments: Loans","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, further to the reply by Viscount Younger of Leckie on 13 December (HL Deb, cols 1552–4), whether any Government body, other than the Student Loans Company, provides loans on which interest is charged at six per cent or more per annum.","false","Biography information for Lord Morris of Aberavon",,"Lord Morris of Aberavon","HL4322"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809622","HM Treasury","false","2017-12-21","<p>The Financial Services Compensation Scheme publishes details of interventions it has undertaken to protect depositors, which can be found on the fscs.org.uk website. The Scheme announced that it had protected the savings of members in five credit unions which entered default in 2016.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2017-12-21T11:09:17.57Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809622/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809622/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809622/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-12-19","Credit Unions: Financial Services Compensation Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many credit unions were subject to intervention by the financial services compensation scheme to protect savers in 2016.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","120256"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809623","Home Office","false","2018-01-05","<p>The Government expects police forces to consider very seriously the findings and recommendations in the Safer Bristol Partnership’s December 2017 report into the murder of Bijan Ebrahimi in 2013.</p><p>The Independent Police Complaints Commission also published a report in July 2017 on Avon and Somerset Constabulary’s contact with Mr Ebrahimi prior to his murder. Where the IPCC has investigated, reported and issued learning recommendations, the police and other agencies are required to respond setting out what action they are taking or to explain why no action is being taken.</p><p>In its published response to the IPCC’s report, Avon and Somerset Constabulary set out the steps it had taken to improve the way it operates since 2013, including the design and implementation of a new operating model in 2014/15.</p><p>Evidence gathered by the IPCC informed criminal proceedings which resulted in two officers receiving prison sentences. These officers and two others were dismissed following misconduct proceedings brought by Avon and Somerset Constabulary.</p><p>Following publication of the Safer Bristol Partnership’s report, Avon and Somerset Constabulary has issued a statement fully accepting the findings of the report, and re-iterating the steps it has taken, following the IPCC’s report, to transform the way the Constabulary operates to prevent a repeat of what happened to Mr Ebrahimi.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2018-01-05T14:38:49.1Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809623/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809623/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809623/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-12-19","Bijan Ebrahimi","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what steps they will take to ensure that lessons learned from the murder of Bijan Ebrahimi are acted upon by UK police forces.","false","Biography information for Baroness Quin",,"Baroness Quin","HL4323"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809624","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-12-22","<p>All existing Disability Living Allowance claimants who were aged 16 to 64 on 8 April 2013, or who reach age 16 thereafter, are being invited to claim Personal Independence Payment (PIP). With the exception of those claiming under the special provisions for people who are terminally ill, all claims to PIP are treated in the same way and are subject to an assessment of needs to determine entitlement and the correct rate to pay benefit.</p><p> </p><p>Most people will be asked to attend a face-to-face consultation with a trained independent assessor. However, we recognise that attending a face-to-face assessment can be a stressful experience for some people, which is why we do not carry out face-to-face consultations where there is enough existing evidence to determine benefit entitlement. Furthermore, where a face-to-face consultation is required, that can take place in a claimant’s home if they are unable to travel to an assessment centre. We and our Assessment Providers also encourage claimants to bring another person with them to consultations where they would find this helpful to, for example, reassure them or to help them during the consultation.</p>",,"Baroness Buscombe",,"2017-12-22T12:21:22.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809624/answer","Biography information for Baroness Buscombe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809624/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809624/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-12-19","Personal Independence Payment: Congenital Central Hypoventilation Syndrome","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they have made special arrangements for people with Congenital Central Hypoventilation Syndrome who are transferring from Disability Living Allowance to Personal Independence Payments.","false","Biography information for Lord Rooker",,"Lord Rooker","HL4324"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809625","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-01-08","<p>The role of the widely respected inspectorates in England and Wales, Scotland and Northern Ireland is critical in ensuring that there is an objective and challenging assessment of individual prisons and criminal justice systems.</p><p> </p><p>There are a range of reports that are issued by these independent scrutiny bodies, including inspection reports, annual reports, thematic reports, monitoring reports and action plan reviews. Some of these reports are joint publications, for example Criminal Justice Inspection Northern Ireland and Her Majesty’s Inspectorate of Prisons recently conducted an inspection of HMP Magilligan which was published on 12<sup>th</sup> December 2017.</p><p> </p><p>We are always looking at ways to maximise the impact of independent scrutiny on our prisons to improve the outcomes for prisoners. The Inspectorates are independent and it is for them to consider how best to share their learning and best practice.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2018-01-08T17:33:27.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809625/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809625/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809625/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-12-19","HM Inspectorate of Prisons","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, if his Department will conduct an assessment of the range of reports issued by Her Majesty's Inspectorate of Prisons in England and Wales compared with the reports issued by its counterpart bodies in Scotland and Northern Ireland.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","120257"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809626","Home Office","false","2017-12-21","<p>We do not ask individuals referred to the UK for resettlement by the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) to disclose their sexual orientation, therefore this is not recorded unless it is a factor in their need for protection.</p><p>Individuals who require protection because of their sexual orientation are likely to be referred to us under UNCHR’s vulnerability category of ‘Legal and/or Physical Protection Needs’. We have no plans to change this approach.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-12-21T16:31:20.88Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809626/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809626/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809626/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-12-19","Refugees: Syria","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, further to their response to the House of Commons International Development Committee's report Syrian refugees crisis (1st report, 2015–16, HC Paper 463 and 5th Special Report, 2015–16, HC Paper 902), whether they plan to record the sexual orientation or gender identity of people referred to the UK for resettlement if and when it is declared by the refugee.","false","Biography information for Lord Scriven",,"Lord Scriven","HL4325"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809627","Home Office","false","2017-12-21","<p>In all of the countries from which we resettle refugees fleeing the Syrian conflict, the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) has undertaken significant efforts to ensure that LGBTI individuals are able to register. These include establishing mobile registration units, outreach teams and help desks for areas where different minority groups are concentrated. This is all part of an effort to facilitate registration for those refugees who, for whatever reason, cannot or choose not to access the main registration offices.</p><p>In addition to training its staff on LGBTI issues, UNHCR also works closely with partner non-governmental organisations (NGOs) supporting the LGBTI community in the region to facilitate registration, ensure access to services and explore available durable solutions, which may include consideration for resettlement. The NGOs have autonomy to refer such cases to UNHCR where particular protection concerns exist.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-12-21T16:50:19.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809627/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809627/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809627/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-12-19","Refugees: Syria","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what steps have been taken to intensify outreach to LGBT refugees who may be in need of resettlement under the Vulnerable Persons Resettlement Scheme.","false","Biography information for Lord Scriven",,"Lord Scriven","HL4326"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809628","Department of Health","false","2018-01-08","<p>No such assessment has been made. However, there are a number of programmes funded by the Government which are likely to have a differential impact on men’s health, given evidence that men may be less likely to seek help with health problems. For example, the Government has funded the Time to Change anti-stigma campaign, which challenges attitudes towards mental health. Time to Change launched the ‘In your corner’ campaign this year which is specifically aimed at encouraging men to talk about mental health. Another example is heart disease: the British Heart Foundation states that men are more likely to develop cardiovascular disease at an earlier age than women.</p><p> </p><p>In 2016 NHS RightCare launched the Cardiovascular Disease Prevention Optimal Value Pathway, which aims to reduce unwarranted variation to improve people's health and lessen inequalities in health access, experience and outcomes. In addition, local authorities offer the NHS Health Check to all adults aged 40-74 who do not have certain pre-existing health conditions; the Health Check therefore offers an opportunity to engage with men who might otherwise not be seen by health services. Public Health England’s One You campaign aims to improve health by encouraging adults to change their lifestyles and adopt healthier behaviours. In addition, the Men’s Health Forum are a member of the voluntary, community and social enterprise Health and Wellbeing Alliance, a group of 21 organisations and consortia which aims to bring the voice of the sector into policy making in the Department, NHS England and Public Health England.</p><p> </p><p>The life expectancy of both males and females continues to rise; whilst there remains a gap between female and male life expectancy, this gap is closing.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2018-01-08T16:26:41.27Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809628/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809628/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809628/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-12-19","Health: Males","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether his Department has made an assessment of behavioural changes among adult males in reporting their own medical health issues over the last 10 years; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","120258"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809629","Home Office","false","2017-12-21","<p>Details of the marital status and family composition of those arriving under the Vulnerable Persons Resettlement Scheme (VPRS) are not published</p><p>A total of 9,394 people have been resettled under the VPRS since the scheme began. Around half of those resettled under the VPRS were under 18 years old, and around half were female.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-12-21T16:50:41.513Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809629/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809629/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809629/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-12-19","Refugees: Syria","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how many single people, couples and families have been resettled to the UK under the Vulnerable Persons Resettlement Scheme.","false","Biography information for Lord Scriven",,"Lord Scriven","HL4327"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809630","Department of Health","false","2017-12-21","<p>A consultation impact assessment, <em>Consultation on an opt-out system of organ and tissue donation</em>, has been published as part of the Government’s public consultation. A copy is attached. This suggests that, when introduced as part of a wider communication and logistical package, opt out systems of consent can be associated with higher donation rates. Important evidence continues to become available from the Welsh Government on impact of the Human Transplantation (Wales) Act 2013, including that a longer period of time is needed to draw firmer conclusions on the impact of the change in the law. The Department invites further evidence to be submitted on factors not considered in the consultation analysis. These will be carefully considered before the Government’s final response to the consultation.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy","HL4329","2017-12-21T15:39:01.573Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809630/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809630/answer","HL4328 and 4329Organ_Donation_Opt-Out_Consultation_Impact_Assessment.pdf","Consultation Impact Assessment","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809630/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-12-19","Organs: Donors","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the Welsh Government's Evaluation of the Human Transplantation (Wales) Act which found that after the change in organ donation law in Wales the quarterly mean average of organ donation fell from 14.6 to 13.4.","false","Biography information for Lord Sheikh",,"Lord Sheikh","HL4328"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809631","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-01-08","<p>Options for the disposal of the Goliath crane are under consideration but no decisions have been taken.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2018-01-08T14:43:07.027Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809631/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809631/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809631/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-12-19","Rosyth Dockyard: Materials Handling Equipment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the current status of the MOD-owned Goliath heavy lift crane at Rosyth is; what estimate he has made of its net disposal value; and what assessment he has made of its potential use in future naval shipbuilding programmes.","false","Biography information for Mr Paul Sweeney","Glasgow North East","Mr Paul Sweeney","120259"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809632","Department of Health","false","2017-12-21","<p>A consultation impact assessment, <em>Consultation on an opt-out system of organ and tissue donation</em>, has been published as part of the Government’s public consultation. A copy is attached. This suggests that, when introduced as part of a wider communication and logistical package, opt out systems of consent can be associated with higher donation rates. Important evidence continues to become available from the Welsh Government on impact of the Human Transplantation (Wales) Act 2013, including that a longer period of time is needed to draw firmer conclusions on the impact of the change in the law. The Department invites further evidence to be submitted on factors not considered in the consultation analysis. These will be carefully considered before the Government’s final response to the consultation.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy","HL4328","2017-12-21T15:39:01.51Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809632/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809632/answer","HL4328 and 4329Organ_Donation_Opt-Out_Consultation_Impact_Assessment.pdf","Consultation Impact Assessment","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809632/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-12-19","Organs: Donors","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the finding that since the introduction of the Human Transplantation (Wales) Act over 178,000 people have opted out of organ donation.","false","Biography information for Lord Sheikh",,"Lord Sheikh","HL4329"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809633","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-01-04","<p>The UK has strong concerns about continued reports of mistreatment of Palestinian minors in Israeli military detention, notably the use of painful restraints and insufficient notification of legal rights. Our Ambassador to Israel raised concerns about this issue with Minister of Justice Shaked on 7 December. The Minister for the Middle East (Alistair Burt) also raised our concerns with the Israeli authorities during his visit to Israel in August 2017. We continue to regularly raise this issue with the Israeli authorities, and to press them to secure improvements to the practices surrounding the military detention of minors.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2018-01-04T16:38:45.45Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809633/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809633/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809633/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-12-19","Israel: Palestinians","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what representations they are making to the government of Israel concerning the reported arrest and abuse of Palestinian minors in relation to unidentified charges.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL4330"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809634","Department of Health","false","2017-12-22","<p>Information held on the average waiting time for children and young people being treated in National Health Service funded secondary mental health services is published in NHS England’s Five Year Forward View for Mental Health Dashboard tables. Information for quarter 1 2017/18 (April to June 2017), is available at:</p><p><a href="http://content.digital.nhs.uk/media/25512/Children-and-young-people-mental-health-indicators-Q1-2017-18/xls/Children_and_young_people_mental_health_indicators_(Q1_2017-18).xlsx" target="_blank">http://content.digital.nhs.uk/media/25512/Children-and-young-people-mental-health-indicators-Q1-2017-18/xls/Children_and_young_people_mental_health_indicators_(Q1_2017-18).xlsx</a></p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2017-12-22T14:33:50.373Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809634/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809634/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809634/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-12-19","Mental Health Services: Kirklees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what information his Department holds on the average waiting time for children with mental health issues to receive treatment in Kirklees.","false","Biography information for Thelma Walker","Colne Valley","Thelma Walker","120260"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809635","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-01-02","<p>Our Embassy in Tel Aviv and our Consulate-General in Jerusalem frequently urge the Israeli and Palestinian authorities to take steps to improve conditions in Gaza. We have carried out demarches to this effect, urging Israel to go further in easing movement and access restrictions on Gaza. We also support projects to improve movement and access of people and goods in and out of Gaza through the Global Britain Fund.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2018-01-02T14:21:52.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809635/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809635/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809635/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-12-19","Gaza: Infrastructure","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what representations they are making to the government of Israel to ensure that the building materials and machinery necessary to improve the infrastructure needed for winterisation assistance are allowed into Gaza.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL4331"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809636","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-01-08","<p>The Government shares many of the priorities outlined in the US National Security Strategy published on 18 December 2017, including addressing the challenges posed by North Korea, reducing violent extremism and defeating the remnants of Da'esh, tackling cyber attacks and organised crime, and strengthening the rules-based international system. We welcome the Strategy's restatement of the US commitment to NATO, including Article V of the North Atlantic Treaty, and its recognition that working with Allies such as the UK contributes to collective security. The US and UK are very close allies and partners, with a uniquely broad and deep security relationship, and we will continue to work together on issues vital to the UK's security and prosperity.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2018-01-08T13:23:33.747Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809636/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809636/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809636/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-12-19","USA: National Security","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what is their assessment of the implications for the UK of the recently published United States national security strategy.","false","Biography information for Lord Truscott",,"Lord Truscott","HL4332"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809637","Cabinet Office","false","2018-01-08","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2018-01-08T11:44:12.377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809637/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809637/answer","PQ 120261 UKSA .pdf","UKSA Response ","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809637/answer",,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-12-19","Average Earnings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what the median real earnings were in each region of the UK in each of the last 30 years.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","120261"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809638","Attorney General","false","2018-01-05","<p>The offences under sections 96 and 97 of the Education and Skills Act 2008 came into force, as they relate to independent schools, on 5 January 2015. Since that date two cases have been referred to the Crown Prosecution Service for early investigative advice following which investigations were discontinued. Two further cases have been referred to the Crown Prosecution Service for a charging decision. In both of these latter cases the evidential test under the Code for Crown Prosecutors was not met.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie",,"2018-01-05T12:56:41.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809638/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809638/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809638/answer",,,,,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2017-12-19","Out-of-school Education: Prosecutions","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Keen of Elie on 6 November (HL2408), whether there have been no prosecutions for operating unregistered schools because no cases have been put to the Crown Prosecution Service, or for evidential reasons.","false","Biography information for Lord Warner",,"Lord Warner","HL4333"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809639","Department for Education","false","2018-01-05","<p>It is imperative that Her Majesty’s Chief Inspector and her staff feel able to carry out their responsibilities and report their findings without fear or favour. The Cabinet Office sets security policy for government, which all departments, including Ofsted, follow. Any concerns that Her Majesty’s Chief Inspector or her staff have regarding their personal safety or building security would in the first instance, be discussed with the police who would consider the nature of any threats, provide appropriate security advice and recommend any further measures.</p>",,"Lord Agnew of Oulton",,"2018-01-05T14:55:45.133Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809639/answer","Biography information for Lord Agnew of Oulton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809639/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809639/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-12-19","Ofsted: Security","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what steps they are taking to protect the Chief Inspector of Schools and her staff and offices in the light of threatened attacks following Ofsted's criticism of faith-based schools.","false","Biography information for Lord Warner",,"Lord Warner","HL4334"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809640","HM Treasury","false","2018-01-08","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) does not hold information on the number of customs agents in the UK. HMRC does not authorize customs agents and the role is not defined in Customs legislation. Individuals and companies may appoint third parties or intermediaries to act on their behalf to perform a range of services in the international supply chain including freight forwarders and/or acting as a customs representative and the term can be used to cover each of these services.</p><p> </p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2018-01-08T16:42:16.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809640/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809640/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809640/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-12-19","Customs: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many customs agents there were in the UK in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Peter Dowd","Bootle","Peter Dowd","120262"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809641","Department for Education","false","2018-01-05","<p>The department does not have primary legislation scheduled for this session, therefore the government has no current plans to change Ofsted’s powers in relation to the investigation of unregistered schools.</p><p> </p><p>In January 2016 we announced that we were providing funding to Ofsted to establish a dedicated team of specialist inspectors to investigate such settings. The figures published in Her Majesty’s Chief Inspector’s annual report shows that the work of this team has been highly successful, but the figures also demonstrate that there are far fewer unregistered schools than many had believed to be the case. During a period of one and a half years, from January 2016 to August 2017, the Ofsted team found 38 unregistered schools to be operating; and the team was successful in getting 34 of those 38 to cease operating illegally. The remaining 4 were still under investigation as at August 2017.</p><p> </p><p>The department, working with Ofsted and local authority Directors of Childrens Services, has been drawing up guidance for local authorities on how to tackle unregistered schools. We are expecting to be publishing this guidance in due course.</p>",,"Lord Agnew of Oulton",,"2018-01-05T13:41:13.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809641/answer","Biography information for Lord Agnew of Oulton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809641/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809641/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-12-19","Out-of-school Education","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what steps they intend to take to strengthen Ofsted’s powers to prosecute and close illegal unregistered schools following comments by the Chief Inspector of Schools in her annual report that the current legislation is inadequate; and what guidance they will provide to local authorities regarding steps that can be taken against such schools using (1) health and safety provisions, and (2) child protection measures.","false","Biography information for Lord Warner",,"Lord Warner","HL4335"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809642","HM Treasury","false","2017-12-21","<p>The Government introduced Marriage Allowance in 2015 to recognise marriage and civil partnership in the tax system and to help couples keep more of the money they earn. Those in legally recognised marriages and civil partnerships in the UK are eligible for Marriage Allowance. This includes humanist ceremonies in Scotland.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2017-12-21T14:02:13.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809642/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809642/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809642/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-12-19","Married People: Tax Allowances","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether an English couple married in a humanist ceremony in Scotland are able to claim the Marriage Allowance.","false","Biography information for Lord Warner",,"Lord Warner","HL4336"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809643","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-01-08","<p>Substantial reforms have been made over recent years to control the costs of civil litigation, and to deter fraudulent and unmeritorious claims. In particular, the operation of ‘no win no fee’ conditional fee agreements (CFAs) has been improved by Part 2 of the Legal Aid, Sentencing and Punishment of Offenders (LASPO) Act 2012. The Part 2 reforms, which came into effect in April 2013, also allowed Damages-Based Agreements (DBAs) to be used in civil litigation for the first time.</p><p> </p><p>CFAs and DBAs facilitate access to justice by enabling claims to be brought by those of modest means. The Government recognises that access to justice has to be meaningful for defendants too: the Part 2 and other reforms help to ensure that claims are resolved at more proportionate cost, with the risk of litigation now being borne by claimants rather than defendants, who no longer having to pay inflated legal costs.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is committed to carrying out a post-implementation review of Part 2 of the LASPO Act, to be completed by summer recess 2018.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab","120264","2018-01-08T15:03:42.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809643/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809643/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809643/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-12-19","Trials: Legal Costs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, if he will make it his policy to reform the legal system to ensure that one side does not bear the financial risk associated with taking a case to trial and the other side cannot escape exposure to such risk through Damages Based Agreements and Conditional Fee Agreements.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","120263"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809644","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-01-08","<p>Substantial reforms have been made over recent years to control the costs of civil litigation, and to deter fraudulent and unmeritorious claims. In particular, the operation of ‘no win no fee’ conditional fee agreements (CFAs) has been improved by Part 2 of the Legal Aid, Sentencing and Punishment of Offenders (LASPO) Act 2012. The Part 2 reforms, which came into effect in April 2013, also allowed Damages-Based Agreements (DBAs) to be used in civil litigation for the first time.</p><p> </p><p>CFAs and DBAs facilitate access to justice by enabling claims to be brought by those of modest means. The Government recognises that access to justice has to be meaningful for defendants too: the Part 2 and other reforms help to ensure that claims are resolved at more proportionate cost, with the risk of litigation now being borne by claimants rather than defendants, who no longer having to pay inflated legal costs.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is committed to carrying out a post-implementation review of Part 2 of the LASPO Act, to be completed by summer recess 2018.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab","120263","2018-01-08T15:03:42.45Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809644/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809644/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809644/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-12-19","Trials: Legal Costs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what recent assessment his Department has made of the effect of damages based agreements and conditional fee agreements on the number of fraudulent and unmeritorious claims pursued.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","120264"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809645","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-12-27","<p>The information requested could only be obtained at disproportionate cost. The Government is fully committed to making our prisons deliver safe and decent regimes and is actively taking the measures necessary to ensure that. We are boosting the number of prison officers by 2,500 and we have already reached the halfway mark over the past year with a further 1,211 candidates who have received job offers.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2017-12-27T15:52:41.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809645/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809645/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809645/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-12-19","Prisoners","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the average number of hours per day was that prisoners were kept in cells in each prison in the UK in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","120265"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809646","Department for Transport","false","2018-01-08","<p>I replied on 21 December 2017.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2018-01-08T15:15:39.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809646/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809646/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809646/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-12-19","Members: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when he plans to respond to the letter from The Right hon. Member for Enfield North, dated 24 October 2017, on the development of the Northern Gateway Access Package.","false","Biography information for Joan Ryan","Enfield North","Joan Ryan","120266"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809647","Department for Transport","false","2017-12-21","<p>Since October 2017 to the end of November 2017, there has been one case of alleged bullying and harassment reported to the Driver and Vehicle Standards Agency (DVSA) involving a senior manager (Grade 7 or above). This case is being dealt with formally in accordance with DVSA’s policy and procedures with support from Civil Service Human Resources, who provide a casework service to DVSA.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-12-21T13:28:08.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809647/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809647/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809647/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-12-19","Driver and Vehicle Standards Agency: Bullying","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many DVSA staff have reported incidents of bullying and harassment by senior management since October 2017; and what steps DVSA have taken in response to those reported incidents.","false","Biography information for Mary Glindon","North Tyneside","Mary Glindon","120267"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809648","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-01-18","<p>The number of new ostriches registered with the Animal and Plant Health Agency (APHA) from 2015, 2016 and 2017 was as follows.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>6 customers registered</p></td><td><p>41 ostriches</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>2 customers registered</p></td><td><p>6 ostriches</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017</p></td><td><p>2 customers registered</p></td><td><p>41 ostriches</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="3"><p>88 new ostriches were registered between 2015-2017</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>APHA has 1015 ostriches recorded in Sam (APHA livestock system) across 47 different customers.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2018-01-18T13:29:16.65Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809648/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809648/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809648/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-12-19","Ostriches","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many ostriches were registered with the Animal and Plant Health Agency in (a) 2015, (b) 2016 and (c) 2017.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mr Mark Hendrick","120268"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809649","Department for Education","false","2017-12-22","<p>We are delivering the biggest improvement to the school funding system for well over a decade and our national funding formula will create a fairer system.</p><p>We trust schools to manage their own budgets with the great majority having a cumulative surplus of funds, built up over a number of years. The latest published figures for England’s schools showed an overall cumulative surplus of more than £4 billion (for schools with a cumulative surplus), against a cumulative deficit of less than £300 million.</p><p>We continue to provide support to schools to help them use their resources in the most efficient way, so they can deliver the best value for the taxpayer.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-12-22T17:57:02.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809649/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809649/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809649/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-12-19","Schools: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what the level of financial reserves held by schools in England is.","false","Biography information for Chris Philp","Croydon South","Chris Philp","120269"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809650","Department for Education","false","2017-12-22","<p>Spending on staff as a proportion of the total schools’ budgets has decreased from 77% in 2011/12 to 74% in 2015/16 for academies and from 77% in 2009-10 to 73% 2016-17 for local authority maintained schools.</p><p>In July 2017 we announced an additional £1.3 billion of funding for schools and high needs across 2018-19 and 2019-20, in addition to the schools budget as set out in the 2015 Spending Review. This means funding per pupil for schools and high needs will be maintained in real terms for the next two years.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-12-22T17:59:58.81Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809650/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809650/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809650/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-12-19","Schools: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what comparative assessment her Department has made of the proportion of the schools budget that has been spent on staffing costs in (a) 2010 and (b) 2017.","false","Biography information for Chris Philp","Croydon South","Chris Philp","120270"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809651","Cabinet Office","true","2017-12-21","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-12-21T11:13:31.847Z","2018-01-08T20:54:47.673Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809651/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809651/answer","PQ120271 & PQ120272 UKSA.pdf","UKSA Response ","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809651/answer","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809651/answer/previousversion/31608","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809651/answer/previousversion/31608","PQ120271, 120272 Chris Runane holding (OW) .pdf","UKSA Response ","53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-12-19","Suicide","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what information he holds on which cities in the UK have the highest suicide rates per 100,000 people in each year for which data is available.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","120271"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809652","Cabinet Office","false","2017-12-21","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore","120271","2017-12-21T11:13:31.88Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809652/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809652/answer","PQ120271, 120272 Chris Runane holding (OW) .pdf","UKSA Response ","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809652/answer",,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-12-19","Suicide","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what information he holds on which 100 local authority wards in the UK have the highest suicide rates per 100,000 people in each year for which data is available; and what those suicide rates were.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","120272"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809653","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-01-08","<p>During 2017, as part of normal military prioritisation, the decision was taken not to conduct these exercises.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2018-01-08T16:47:32.783Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809653/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809653/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809653/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-12-19","Military Exercises","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, (a) when and (b) for what reasons the decision was taken to cancel (i) Exercise Black Horse, (ii) Exercise Curry Trail, (iii) Exercise Orange Marauder, (iv) Exercise Southwest Sword and (v) Commando Strike.","false","Biography information for Nia Griffith","Llanelli","Nia Griffith","120273"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809654","Department for Transport","false","2018-01-08","<p>Following consultation, in October 2017, the Government implemented a new five-year night flight regime at Heathrow, which will end in October 2022. This regime limits the number of scheduled movements to an average of sixteen per night for a six and a half hour night period.</p><p> </p><p>The revised draft Airports National Policy Statement (NPS) sets out the Government’s expectation for a six and a half hour ban on scheduled night flights at an expanded Heathrow. Should the revised draft Airports NPS be designated, consideration of any ban, including timings, would be subject to the International Civil Aviation Organisation’s Balanced Approach to noise management, including consultation with local communities and other interested parties.</p><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2018-01-08T14:09:08.053Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809654/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809654/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809654/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-12-19","Heathrow Airport: Night Flying","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the feasibility of imposing an eight hour night flight ban at Heathrow Airport; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Zac Goldsmith","Richmond Park","Zac Goldsmith","120274"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809655","Department for Transport","false","2018-01-08","<p>The revised draft Airports National Policy Statement (NPS) makes clear that any noise envelope at an expanded Heathrow should be tailored to local priorities and include clear noise performance targets. If the revised draft Airports NPS is designated, the design of any noise envelope would be defined in consultation with local communities and relevant stakeholders.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2018-01-08T14:04:40.5Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809655/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809655/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809655/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-12-19","Heathrow Airport: Noise","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether he has made an assessment of the potential merits of establishing a legally binding noise envelope at Heathrow Airport; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Zac Goldsmith","Richmond Park","Zac Goldsmith","120275"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809656","Department for Transport","false","2018-01-08","<p>Following its recent Airspace Policy consultation, the Department implemented changes to its policy on compensation for communities affected by noise as a result of airspace change. The Government will undertake additional consideration of this issue through the new aviation strategy it is currently developing.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2018-01-08T14:01:16.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809656/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809656/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809656/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-12-19","Aviation: Noise","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if his Department will assess the potential merits of changing the boundaries at which communities affected by aircraft noise receive compensation.","false","Biography information for Zac Goldsmith","Richmond Park","Zac Goldsmith","120276"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809657","Department for Transport","false","2018-01-08","<p>There have been no discussions between the Department for Transport and Heathrow Airport on potential changes to Heathrow’s Quieter Homes scheme.</p><p>Whilst the Government sets the guidelines on when it expect airport operators to provide compensation to local communities, decision on how to apply the guidance are for the airport itself.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2018-01-08T13:56:42.18Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809657/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809657/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809657/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-12-19","Heathrow Airport: Noise","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what discussions he has had with Heathrow Airport on potential boundary changes to its Quieter Homes scheme.","false","Biography information for Zac Goldsmith","Richmond Park","Zac Goldsmith","120277"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809658","Department for Transport","false","2018-01-08","<p>The Government believes that the Heathrow Northwest Runway scheme can be delivered without impacting on the UK’s compliance with air quality limit values, given the measures set out in the Government’s air quality plan, and with a suitable package of mitigation measures taken forward by the promoter.</p><p> </p><p>Should the revised draft Airports National Policy Statement be designated, then it would be for the promoter to undertake a detailed assessment of the air quality impacts of the scheme, including during construction, and put forward to the Planning Inspectorate an appropriate package of mitigations that address air quality impacts and demonstrate compliance with air quality obligations.</p><p> </p><p>In order to grant development consent, the Secretary of State would need to be satisfied that, with mitigation, the scheme would be compliant with legal obligations.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2018-01-08T17:41:26.357Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809658/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809658/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809658/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-12-19","Heathrow Airport: Air Pollution","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the potential effect on air quality of the construction of a third runway at Heathrow.","false","Biography information for Zac Goldsmith","Richmond Park","Zac Goldsmith","120278"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809659","Department of Health","false","2017-12-27","<p>The provision of appropriate patient transport services (PTS) in line with national guidance is a matter for local National Health Service commissioners.</p><p> </p><p>The Department is clear that medically eligible patients must have appropriate access to quality PTS to outpatient appointments. The document ‘Eligibility Criteria for Patient Transport Services’ sets out criteria for establishing which patients are eligible for non-emergency PTS. The guidance states that eligible patients should reach appointments in reasonable time and in reasonable comfort, without detriment to their medical condition.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2017-12-27T11:03:11.11Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809659/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809659/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809659/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-12-19","Patients: Transport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, with reference to Age UK’s Painful Journeys campaign, what steps his Department is taking to make travelling to and from hospital easier for older people.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","120279"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809660","Home Office","false","2017-12-21","<p>The Home Office is committed to working co-operatively with local authorities and communities to ensure the sustainability of asylum accommodation contracts.</p><p>Since September 2016 the Home Office has actively engaged with local authorities with a wide range of stakeholders across local government, statutory and third sector as part of the development of the new asylum accommodation contracts and the information obtained through this process has influenced the design of the future service provision. We will continue to engage with local authorities and the wider community throughout the procurement and implementation of the new contracts.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-12-21T16:40:27.737Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809660/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809660/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809660/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-12-19","Asylum: Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if he will take steps to ensure that future asylum accommodation contracts work to ensure the long-term sustainability of the dispersal system through co-operative working with local authorities and communities.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","120280"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809661","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-12-27","<p>As announced by the Chancellor in his budget in November, my officials are working closely with HM Treasury and a call for evidence will be published early in 2018 seeking views on how the tax system or charges could reduce the amount of single-use plastics waste including non-recyclable plastic straws.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-12-27T12:57:13.18Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809661/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809661/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809661/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-12-19","Plastics: Waste","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps his Department is taking to reduce the use of non-recyclable plastic straws.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","120281"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809662","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-01-10","<p>The level of fees charged and collected in a given financial year are a reflection on the amount of activity that is undertaken for the appropriate process at the published charge out rates. These rates have been unaltered for the past three years and the only variable is the amount of activity undertaken by the Animal and Plant Health Agency’s inspectors.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2018-01-10T15:17:27Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809662/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809662/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809662/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-12-19","Animal and Plant Health Agency: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 19 December 2017 to Question 118449, what estimate his Department has made of the change in the amount of money collected in fees by the Animal and Plant Health Agency under the Bovine Semen (England) Regulations 2007, as amended, between 2014 and 2016.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mr Mark Hendrick","120282"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809663","Department for Transport","false","2018-01-08","<p>The revenue paid to the Department for the Thameslink Southern and Great Northern franchise is shown in the Go Ahead group accounts: <a href="https://www.go-ahead.com/en/investors/results-reports-presentations.html" target="_blank">https://www.go-ahead.com/en/investors/results-reports-presentations.html</a>. The Department does not break down the revenue into individual brands.</p><p> </p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2018-01-08T14:59:30.99Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809663/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809663/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809663/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-12-19","Govia Thameslink Railway","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how much has accrued to the public purse in fare revenues from the GTR franchise agreement for each rail period since the beginning of that franchise.","false","Biography information for Lloyd Russell-Moyle","Brighton, Kemptown","Lloyd Russell-Moyle","120283"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809664","Department for Transport","false","2018-01-08","<p>The revenue paid to the Department for the Thameslink Southern and Great Northern franchise is shown in the Go Ahead group accounts: <a href="https://www.go-ahead.com/en/investors/results-reports-presentations.html" target="_blank">https://www.go-ahead.com/en/investors/results-reports-presentations.html</a>. The Department does not break down the revenue into individual brands.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2018-01-08T14:54:07.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809664/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809664/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809664/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-12-19","Govia Thameslink Railway","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what money has accrued to the public purse from rail revenues from the Southern section of the GTR franchise for each rail period since the beginning of that franchise.","false","Biography information for Lloyd Russell-Moyle","Brighton, Kemptown","Lloyd Russell-Moyle","120284"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809665","Department for Transport","false","2018-01-08","<p>Govia Thameslink Trains Limited has advised that the loss to date of farebox revenues arising from official industrial action on GTR services is £22.2m.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2018-01-08T15:39:06.15Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809665/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809665/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809665/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-12-19","Govia Thameslink Railway: Industrial Disputes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference the Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State’s letter to the Chair of the Transport Committee of 17 November 2016, what the loss to date is of farebox revenues arising from official industrial action on GTR.","false","Biography information for Lloyd Russell-Moyle","Brighton, Kemptown","Lloyd Russell-Moyle","120285"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809666","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-12-29","<p>The Government is committed to tackling fly-tipping at all levels. The maximum penalty on indictment for fly-tipping is imprisonment of up to five years or a potentially unlimited fine. It is for local authorities to use the full range of powers available to them and ensure they prioritise resources to tackling this issue.</p><p> </p><p>We worked with the Sentencing Council to strengthen Guidelines for environmental offences in 2014. We will continue to work with the appropriate people in the court system to ensure sentencing levels act as an effective deterrent.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-12-29T11:41:55.21Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809666/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809666/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809666/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-12-19","Fly-tipping: Sentencing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs whether he plans to increase the length of sentences for repeat fly-tipping offenders; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Ms Nusrat Ghani","Wealden","Ms Nusrat Ghani","120286"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809667","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-12-29","<p>The Ministry of Justice records details of reoffending, which can be found at: <a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/proven-reoffending-statistics-october-2015-to-december-2015" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/statistics/proven-reoffending-statistics-october-2015-to-december-2015</a>.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-12-29T11:36:51.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809667/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809667/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809667/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-12-19","Fly-tipping: Reoffenders","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what information his Department holds on the reoffending rate for people convicted of fly-tipping.","false","Biography information for Ms Nusrat Ghani","Wealden","Ms Nusrat Ghani","120287"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809668","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-01-08","<p>In 2014 the Sentencing Council introduced a new sentencing guideline for environmental crimes including fly-tipping. The guidelines were published to ensure a consistent approach to these offences is taken by courts in England and Wales. Requests for further guidance were received by the Sentencing Council from the National Fly Tipping Prevention Group, chaired by Defra, and the Environment Agency. This was due to concerns that the fines were not high enough to reflect the seriousness of the offences committed or to have a deterrent effect, and that there was an inconsistency in fine levels across the country.</p><p> </p><p>The guidelines encourage magistrates to make more use of the highest levels of fines for some of the more serious offences that come before the courts. It also helps sentencers more easily pitch a fine that is proportionate to the means of the offender.</p><p> </p><p>The Sentencing Council reviewed the effectiveness of the guidelines in 2016. The assessment showed that the level of fines for organisations has risen, but fines for individuals have not seen the same increase. Fines are the most common sentences passed for these offences, since the offences are motivated by making a profit or saving money. However, custody remains the starting point for the most serious types of individual offenders who deliberately commit a crime that causes significant or major harm.</p><p> </p><p>The penalties for fly-tipping are on summary conviction: imprisonment for a term not exceeding 12 months or a fine or both; and on conviction on Indictment: imprisonment for a term not exceeding five years or a fine or both. The removal in 2015 of the £5,000 cap for maximum fines that magistrate’s courts can impose, means that magistrates can hand down an unlimited fine for a fly-tipping summary offences.</p><p> </p><p>In May 2016 we introduced fixed penalty notices of up to £400 for small-scale fly-tipping. This provided local authorities with an alternative to prosecutions and take a more proportionate enforcement response.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2018-01-08T18:29:16.877Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809668/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809668/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809668/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-12-19","Fly-tipping: Sentencing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment he has made of the effectiveness of (a) custodial sentences, (b) fines and (c) community sentences in deterring fly-tipping.","false","Biography information for Ms Nusrat Ghani","Wealden","Ms Nusrat Ghani","120288"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809669","Department for Transport","false","2018-01-08","<p>Govia Thameslink Trains Limited has advised that the loss to date of farebox revenues arising from official industrial action on GTR services is £22.2m.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2018-01-08T15:36:21.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809669/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809669/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809669/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-12-19","Govia Thameslink Railway: Industrial Disputes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State’s letter to the Chair of the Transport Select Committee of 17 November 2016, what the loss to date in farebox revenue has been which has arisen from alleged official industrial action on GTR.","false","Biography information for Lloyd Russell-Moyle","Brighton, Kemptown","Lloyd Russell-Moyle","120289"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809670","Department for Transport","false","2018-01-08","<p>The compensation payments made by Train Operating Companies (TOC) to passengers up to 2016/17 are published on the GOV.UK website, see following link: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/train-operating-companies-passengers-charter-compensation" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/train-operating-companies-passengers-charter-compensation</a>.</p><p> </p><p>The funding of compensation payments depends on the franchise agreement that the TOC has with the DfT and whether or not the TOC is paying the Department for Transport profit share or is eligible for revenue support.</p><p> </p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2018-01-08T14:49:26.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809670/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809670/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809670/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-12-19","Railways: Compensation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Parliamentary Under Secretary of State’s letter of the Chair of the Transport Select Committee of 17 November 2016, how much has been paid to customers to date under the Delay Repay passenger compensation scheme to date; and who is responsible for funding those payments.","false","Biography information for Lloyd Russell-Moyle","Brighton, Kemptown","Lloyd Russell-Moyle","120290"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809671","Department for Education","false","2018-01-09","<p>The Resource Accounting and Budgeting (RAB) charge for fee loans for part-time higher education undergraduate students in 2017/18 is estimated to be around 40%, following the decisions to increase the repayment threshold for post-2012 student loans to £25,000 from April 2018 and to freeze tuition fees in the 2018/19 academic year at the same level as in 2017/18.</p><p> </p><p>The government subsidy, represented by the RAB charge, is a conscious investment in young people and the long-term skills capacity of the economy.</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton",,"2018-01-09T14:24:55.963Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809671/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809671/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809671/answer","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809671/answer/previousversion/33108","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809671/answer/previousversion/33108",,,"60","Education","Education","2017-12-19","Students: Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, with reference to table 1.9 of Autumn Budget 2017, what estimate he has made of level of Resource Accounting and Budgeting required for undergraduate part-time student loans as a result of the rise in tuition fees to £9250 and the proposed changes to the student loan repayment threshold.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","120291"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809672","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-12-21","<p>The Department has already in place recruitment processes to attract Community Partners as part of the Enhanced Support Offer, as announced in the Improving Lives: The Work, Health and Disability Green Paper (published October 2016). The Department has and continues to pursue direct secondments from representative organisations, covering the whole range of disabilities. The Department has also and continues to pursue open recruitment, and it is a standard requirement of the recruitment panels that they have knowledge of or lived experience of disability issues.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-12-21T15:48:17.753Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809672/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809672/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809672/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-12-19","Work and Health Programme: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions what steps his Department is taking to (a) encourage disabled people to apply to become Community Partners for Jobcentre Plus under the Work and Health Programme and (b) ensure that the recruitment process will include panel members who have a lived experience of disability.","false","Biography information for Marsha De Cordova","Battersea","Marsha De Cordova","120292"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809673","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-12-28","<p>HMS QUEEN ELIZABETH is undergoing a programme of sea trials to find any teething problems and rectifying them. Sea trials will continue as scheduled in the New Year. There has been no damage caused to the ship by the leak. Any costs to repair it will be borne by the Aircraft Carrier Alliance and there will be no additional cost to the British taxpayer.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","120294","2017-12-28T12:22:42.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809673/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809673/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809673/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-12-19","HMS Queen Elizabeth","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what estimate his Department has made of the total cost to repair the leak on HMS Queen Elizabeth.","false","Biography information for Jamie Stone","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","Jamie Stone","120293"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809674","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-12-28","<p>HMS QUEEN ELIZABETH is undergoing a programme of sea trials to find any teething problems and rectifying them. Sea trials will continue as scheduled in the New Year. There has been no damage caused to the ship by the leak. Any costs to repair it will be borne by the Aircraft Carrier Alliance and there will be no additional cost to the British taxpayer.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","120293","2017-12-28T12:22:42.13Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809674/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809674/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809674/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-12-19","HMS Queen Elizabeth","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what estimate he has made of the cost to repair any damage caused by the recent leak on HMS Queen Elizabeth.","false","Biography information for Jamie Stone","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","Jamie Stone","120294"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809675","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-12-28","<p>The UK has taken delivery of 14 F-35B Lightning II aircraft between 2012 and 2017. The total unit flyaway cost for these aircraft is $1920 million.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2017-12-28T13:16:24.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809675/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809675/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809675/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-12-19","Joint Strike Fighter Aircraft","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the cost to the public purse is of the recent order of 14 F-35 fighter jets.","false","Biography information for Jamie Stone","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","Jamie Stone","120295"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809676","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-01-08","<p>Defra and the devolved administrations (DAs) are the regulatory bodies responsible for decisions on the release of genetically modified organisms (GMOs) into the environment. The Food Standards Agency (FSA) in England, Wales and Northern Ireland and Food Standards Scotland lead on the marketing of GMOs as food or animal feed products. Where licensing decisions are currently taken as part of a centralised EU process, the intention is for the EU rules to be converted into UK law so that a similar regulatory framework will apply after the UK’s withdrawal from the EU. Discussions are ongoing between Defra, the FSA and DAs on how best to convert the EU arrangements.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2018-01-08T13:28:27.04Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809676/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809676/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809676/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-12-19","Genetically Modified Organisms: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what advice he will be offering UK regulatory bodies on the licensing of GMOs after the UK’s exit from the EU.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","120296"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809677","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2018-01-09","<p>Ministers from across Government are speaking with stakeholders from a variety of sectors, to understand their concerns and priorities regarding our EU exit. As part of this process, we have engaged with a range of think tanks.</p><p><strong><br></strong>Details of Ministerial meetings are published in the Department’s Quarterly Transparency Returns, which are publicly available on <a href="http://gov.uk/" target="_blank">GOV.UK</a>.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2018-01-09T15:41:31.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809677/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809677/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809677/answer",,,,,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2017-12-19","Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, whether his Department has held meetings with (a) the Legatum Institute and (b) Barnabus Reynolds/Politeia on market liberalisation to prepare for the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","120297"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809678","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-12-27","<p>No one should ever have to sleep rough. That is why this Government has committed to halving rough sleeping by 2022 and eliminating it altogether by 2027.</p><p>The newly formed Rough Sleeping and Homelessness Reduction Taskforce will drive forward the implementation of a cross-Government strategy to achieve this.</p><p>At Autumn Budget 2017, we announced £28 million of funding to pilot the Housing First approach for some of the country’s most entrenched rough sleepers. This funding forms part of the £1 billion that the Government has allocated until 2020 to prevent and reduce homelessness and rough sleeping.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-12-27T10:32:07.44Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809678/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809678/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809678/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-12-19","Sleeping Rough","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what information his Department holds on how many people have died while sleeping rough in each of the last seven years; and what steps the Government is taking to help prevent people from becoming seriously ill or dying while sleeping rough.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","120298"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809679","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-12-29","<p>None. This is a devolved matter.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-12-29T11:19:55.91Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809679/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809679/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809679/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-12-19","Agriculture: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what discussions his Department has had with the representatives of the Northern Ireland Assembly on soil and water pollution from intensive pig and poultry farms.","false","Biography information for Paul Girvan","South Antrim","Paul Girvan","120299"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809680","Department for International Trade","false","2017-12-28","<p>The Department for International Trade has met the Legatum Institute on a number of occasions since its formation, at Ministerial and official level, as it does with a number of think tanks. These meetings covered a variety of topics.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-12-28T12:30:32.06Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809680/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809680/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809680/answer",,,,,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-12-19","Trade","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, how many meetings he or his Department have had with (a) the Legatum Institute and (b) Barnabus Reynolds/Politieia on market liberalisation following the UK’s decision to leave the EU.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","120300"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809681","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-12-22","<p>There will continue to be a place in UK agriculture for all sustainable production systems that meet our high environmental and welfare standards. We are committed to working with the industry to ensure a vibrant and productive future for all agricultural sectors as we prepare to leave the European Union. This is a once in a lifetime opportunity to develop policies that support innovation, increase agricultural productivity, and improve the efficiency with which we use natural resources.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-12-22T12:34:46.433Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809681/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809681/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809681/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-12-19","Agriculture: Competition","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps the Government plans to take to increase the capacity of smaller farms to compete with large intensive farms.","false","Biography information for Paul Girvan","South Antrim","Paul Girvan","120301"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809682","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-12-22","<p>The use of the Balanced Scorecard approach becomes mandatory for all central government departments and their agencies as existing contracts are renewed. This has now been enshrined in the updated Crown Commercial Service Facilities Management (FM) Framework which becomes effective early in 2018. The FM Framework is updated every 4 years.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-12-22T12:29:53.253Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809682/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809682/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809682/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-12-19","Food: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what the timeline for introducing the balanced scorecard approach to public procurement decisions for food and catering services is.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","120302"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809683","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-12-22","<p>The Government has a manifesto commitment to ensure that a third of goods and services procured by departments are supplied by Small and Medium Enterprises (SME). We are delivering this in respect of food and catering services through the Plan for Public Procurement: Food and Catering Services, published in 2014.</p><p> </p><p>The Plan simplifies the public procurement process and opens up the market to more SMEs and local producers by providing a level playing field on which UK producers can compete. It provides tools, including the Balanced Scorecard (BSC), to help contracting parties to balance a range of criteria beneficial to the consumer, the environment, and to producers. These include embedding UK production standards, encouraging seasonality of fresh produce and calling for menus which celebrate the provenance of the food.</p><p> </p><p>One of the BSC tools, the online market place, was launched on 11 October 2017 and will be used by businesses to showcase their products and services to procurers and to the rest of the supply chain.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-12-22T12:29:59.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809683/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809683/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809683/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-12-19","Food: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps the Government is taking to support (a) SME’s and (b) British farmers through public procurement.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","120303"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809684","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-12-22","<p>The Plan for Public Procurement through the Balanced Scorecard helps contracting parties to balance a range of criteria including provenance, seasonality, production standards, and cost. The Plan does not mandate any specific diets, but has the flexibility to allow contracting parties to cater for any type of diet.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-12-22T12:33:22.707Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809684/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809684/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809684/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-12-19","Food: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether public procurement processes require caterers to meet the needs of those whose diets are (a) vegetarian (b) vegan and (c) gluten free.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","120304"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809685","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-12-22","<p>The use of the Balanced Scorecard approach becomes mandatory for central government departments and their agencies as existing contracts are renewed.</p><p> </p><p>Its use is also highly recommended for other public sector bodies, but cannot be mandated because responsibility for procurement decisions is delegated to local level.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-12-22T12:26:38.347Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809685/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809685/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809685/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-12-19","Public Sector: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if he will make Government buying standards for public procurement mandatory across the whole of the public sector.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","120305"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809686","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-01-08","<p>The Eatwell Plate (the forerunner of the Eatwell Guide) is referenced under the detailed Health and Wellbeing criteria (Section 2.1) of the Balanced Scorecard (BSC) tool in the Plan for Public Procurement of Food and Catering Service 2014.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2018-01-08T13:29:39.28Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809686/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809686/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809686/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-12-19","Food: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether the Government plans to include the Eatwell Guide into Government buying standards on the public procurement of food and drink.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","120306"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809687","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-01-08","<p>Whether it is an appeal to the First-tier Tribunal or the Upper Tribunal, the Department does not offer payments to claimants to withdraw their Personal Independence Payment appeals.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2018-01-08T14:55:52.683Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809687/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809687/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809687/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-12-19","Personal Independence Payment: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether there are circumstances in which his Department offers payments to claimants who withdraw their appeals against decisions on personal independence payments; how many such payments have been made; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Ms Karen Buck","Westminster North","Ms Karen Buck","120307"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809688","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-01-08","<p>The Government continues to press to ensure full implementation of the UN Security Council Presidential Statement proposed by the UK and secured on 6 November. The UK will continue to lobby Burma and Bangladesh to ensure that Rohingya refugee returns are safe, voluntary and in dignity; support Bangladesh in its generous effort to host the refugees; work with international partners to bring the perpetrators of human rights violations in Rakhine to justice and to press Burma to allow the UN Fact Finding Mission free and unhindered access; encourage the Burmese Government to implement in full the recommendations of the Rakhine Advisory Commission and make Rakhine safe for Rohingya by ending discrimination with immediate effect.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2018-01-08T14:59:02.49Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809688/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809688/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/809688/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-12-19","Rohingya","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what long-term plans his Department has to tackle the crisis for the Rohingya people in Myanmar and Bangladesh.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","120308"
